                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1084">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.113/467a.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">American Ambassador</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-04-24T11:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 24, 1912—11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>You may intimate to the Minister for Foreign Affairs that unless a more obliging
                    disposition is shown and permission is soon given for importation of arms,
                    ammunition, for Americans at Guadalajara, Tampico, and in Sonora, this
                    Department will not recommend further exceptions to the President’s proclamation
                    of March 14, 1912, in favor of the Mexican Federal Government.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Knox.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
